Data Acquisition

All of the inital data was obtained through a python web scraper and inserted into a MySQL database. In the database, post categories are stored with a numeric code. The translations of these codes to their actual name were manually created in a CSV file and will be inserted into a seperate table below for later JOIN commands.

Connecting to the MySQL Server

library(RMySQL)
## Loading required package: DBI
con <- dbConnect(MySQL(),
         user="root", password=".",
         dbname="letsrun", host="localhost")

Posts per day

Run some SQL to get the count of posts per day.

posts_per_day <- dbGetQuery(con, "SELECT count(*) as count, date(datestamp) as date FROM posts GROUP BY date(datestamp);")
dbDisconnect(con)
## [1] TRUE
posts_per_day

Data Exploration

Exploratory data plots

Some plots to help visualize the data. Mainly focused with posting rates so that data will be explored. ### Post per day

library(ggplot2)
posts_per_day$date <- as.Date(posts_per_day$date)
qplot(x=date, y=count, data=posts_per_day, xlab = "Date", ylab = "Number of Posts")

From this graph we can initially identify a few outliers. Most notable the point around 1980, and the two points around 2005. Examining the data we can see that the point in 1980 was likely got corrupted somehow and got dated to 1985-07-27. #### Removing 1985-07-27

posts_per_day <- posts_per_day[!(posts_per_day$date == "1985-07-27"),]

Now to view the extreme outliers we can use the following

head(posts_per_day[order(posts_per_day$count, decreasing = TRUE),], n = 20)

We can say with certainty that 2005-01-01 is an extreme outlier (with over 11,000 posts that day) and posts likely got backdated to that timestamp on the forum for some reason. The other date in question is 2005-08-02 with 3442 posts that day. That is not an extreme value compared to posts in more recent years however at the time that appears to be an extreme and likely is a misrepresented value. Both values will be replaced by a ten day average surrounding them.

Fixing 2005-01-01

# get average of 5 days before and after
ten_day <- posts_per_day[posts_per_day$date >= "2004-12-27" & posts_per_day$date <= "2005-01-06" & posts_per_day$date != "2005-01-01",]
ten_day_average <- as.integer(mean(ten_day$count))
posts_per_day[posts_per_day$date == "2005-01-01", "count"] <- ten_day_average

Fixing 2005-08-02

For this date instead of taking the average of the 5 dates surrounding it in either direciton, I will just be taking the preceding 5 dates. In August of 2005, the World Championships for Track and Field were held from August 6-14 so taking an average including those dates wouldnt reflect a normal value the best.

# get average of 10 days surrounding and set it
ten_day <- posts_per_day[posts_per_day$date >= "2005-07-23" & posts_per_day$date <= "2005-08-01",]
ten_day_average <- as.integer(mean(ten_day$count))
posts_per_day[posts_per_day$date == "2005-08-02", "count"] <- ten_day_average

Removing incomplete data

Only take complete years of data so take 2003 through 2017 only.

posts_per_day <- posts_per_day[posts_per_day$date >= "2003-01-01" & posts_per_day$date < "2018-01-01",]
qplot(x=date, y=count, data=posts_per_day, xlab = "Date", ylab = "Number of Posts")

After cleaning the data a bit we can see a much clearer picture of what the usage of the site looks like. At first glance you may say those seemingly vertical lines are an outlier however those two lines represent the Olympics in 2012 and 2016, and such an increase in site usage is expected.

Posts per month and year

To simplify the data further lets take a look at the posts per month. This is essentially a moving average for each month of data.

month.year <- strftime(posts_per_day$date, "%Y/%m")
posts_per_month_year <- aggregate(posts_per_day$count ~ month.year, FUN = sum)
posts_per_month_year <- setNames(posts_per_month_year, c("month.year", "count"))
lvls <- posts_per_month_year$month.year
ggplot(posts_per_month_year, aes(x=month.year, y=count)) + geom_point() + xlab("Date") + ylab("Number of Posts") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))  + scale_x_discrete(breaks=lvls[seq(1,length(lvls),by=10)])

Posts per month

month <- strftime(posts_per_day$date, "%m")
posts_per_month <- aggregate(posts_per_day$count ~ month, FUN = sum)
posts_per_month <- setNames(posts_per_month, c("month", "count"))
qplot(x=month, y=count, data=posts_per_month, xlab="Month", ylab = "Number of Posts")

This is a very interesting graph as it suggests a strong seasonality aspect to the usage of the site likely linked to the prevalence of the outdoor track season and global track events such as the Olympics and World Championships.

Models

ARIMA

This guide along with the wikipedia article on ARIMA were used to aid in learning how to use the model. https://www.datascience.com/blog/introduction-to-forecasting-with-arima-in-r-learn-data-science-tutorials An ARIMA model will be fitted to previous time series data and be used to forecast future site usage

library('forecast')
library('tseries')

# create a time series for the monthly moving average
count_ma <- ts(posts_per_month_year$count, deltat = 1/12)
# create a seasonal decomposition of the time seires
decomp = stl(count_ma, s.window="periodic")
plot(decomp)

We can see from the exploratory graphs and from the trend graph above that posts increase over time and the seasonal graph shows a seasonal trend (as expected from the prior seasonal graphs). As above it shows the summer time highs and winter lows. #### Model Creation We are using the forecast package to automatically return the best ARIMA model.

arima_model<-auto.arima(count_ma, seasonal=TRUE)
arima_model
## Series: count_ma 
## ARIMA(1,1,1)(0,0,2)[12] 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ma1    sma1    sma2
##       0.5583  -0.8710  0.4125  0.1184
## s.e.  0.1059   0.0648  0.0780  0.0679
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 18290645:  log likelihood=-1749.78
## AIC=3509.55   AICc=3509.9   BIC=3525.49

We can see auto.arima chose to use parameters (1,1,1) which means the model uses a differencing degree of 1 (the number of times the data has had past values subctracted which in this case eliminates the increasing trend and establishes stationarity), an autoregresssive term of first lag (use previous period to predict the next period) and a moving average model of order 1. The next group of parameters selected are for the seasonality componenet which suggest the differencing degree is 0, the lag is 0 and the model is of order 2 (used in the forecast formula). https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autoregressive_integrated_moving_average #### Forecast

# forecast 12 months forward
fcast <- forecast(arima_model, h=12)
fcast

Forecast Plot

plot(fcast, col="red")

#### Evaluation From the print out of the values of fcast above we can see it generally follows the seasonality componenets that we saw from the exploratory graphs above. We see a high in August and a low in February and appropriate trends leading up to and leaving this months as we previously saw.

accuracy(fcast)
##                    ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE      MASE
## Training set 365.9051 4216.939 2874.845 0.5512521 7.948284 0.5294682
##                     ACF1
## Training set 0.004276277

The ARIMA model gives a Mean Percentage Error of .55% which is low (signifying a good fit).

plot(fcast$x, col="red")
lines(fitted(fcast), col="blue")

This graph shows the original data in red overlayed with the model prediction in blue representing a very close fit which supports our previous observations of a low MPE. The ARIMA model parameters that were chosen to be best use a lag term of 1 which in this case means it uses the previous months data to predict the next time slot. Thats why when there are big spikes in usage the ARIMA model doesnt reflect that until the next months data point. This is a weakness of the model and does not allow it to make very far future predictions as the farther it makes predictions the less noisy the data will become and the more it will approach a constant value.

fcast_far <- forecast(arima_model, h=48)
plot(fcast_far, col="red")
